[
    {
        "content": "<p>Let <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>S</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">S</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">S</span></span></span></span> be a (possibly infinite) set.  Then what is the structure of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi mathvariant=\"script\">P</mi><mtext>fin</mtext></msup><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>S</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal{P}^{\\text{fin}}(S)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.0991em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08222em;\">P</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8491em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord text mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">fin</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">S</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>, if we care about the operations of union, intersection, and set difference?</p>\n<p>It is not a Boolean algebra because it doesn't include <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>S</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">S</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">S</span></span></span></span>.  It is like a semiring in measure theory.</p>\n<p>We could equivalently say that the operations we care about are intersection and symmetric difference.  Then it is a <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">Z</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{Z}_2</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8389em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbb\">Z</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3011em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:0em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">2</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>-algebra.  But that's not enough!  We also need the multiplication to be associative, commutative, and idempotent.  Is that enough?</p>\n<p>We could also say that it is a join-semilattice with a \"difference\" operation that we define somehow -- does this have a name?</p>\n<p>Is there some better way to describe this structure?</p>",
        "id": 400177310,
        "sender_full_name": "Joshua Meyers",
        "timestamp": 1699032241
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I may be mixed up, but I think <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi mathvariant=\"script\">P</mi><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">f</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi></mrow></msup><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>S</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal{P}^{\\mathrm{fin}}(S)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.0991em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08222em;\">P</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8491em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathrm mtight\">fin</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">S</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> is the free <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/join-semilattice\">[[join-semilattice]]</a> on the set <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>S</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">S</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">S</span></span></span></span>.  There's a monad on Set for join-semilattices, since they can be described using operations obeying equations, i.e. not mentioning the order structure.  See the link for how.</p>",
        "id": 400178413,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1699032687
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The link talks more about the free join-semilattice on a poset, but I think this can be specialized to prove the result I just claimed, thinking of a set as a discrete poset.</p>",
        "id": 400178601,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1699032777
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yes that is true! But what if you want to consider set difference and/or symmetric difference part of the structure?</p>",
        "id": 400189068,
        "sender_full_name": "Joshua Meyers",
        "timestamp": 1699037335
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>As a matter of fact, how do you even get binary intersections this way?</p>",
        "id": 400190106,
        "sender_full_name": "Joshua Meyers",
        "timestamp": 1699037804
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I don't have a canonical reference for this but I would call it a \"locally Boolean algebra\", meaning roughly that the elements that are <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo>≤</mo><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\le A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7719em;vertical-align:-0.136em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">≤</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span> for some fixed <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span> form a Boolean algebra (and so in particular an element <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>B</mi><mo>≤</mo><mi>A</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">B \\le A</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8193em;vertical-align:-0.136em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">≤</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span></span></span></span> has a complement <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>A</mi><mo>∖</mo><mi>B</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">A \\setminus B</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">∖</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05017em;\">B</span></span></span></span> within this algebra, from which we can build the other operations you mention).</p>",
        "id": 400194563,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1699039950
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"280784\">@Joshua Meyers</span> It's just dumb luck that the free join-semilattice turns out to be a distributive lattice, basically. Well, maybe an explanation is that any finite number of elements live in a finite bounded sub-join-semilattice, and such a thing always also has meets, by, if you want to be annoying, the adjoint functor theorem.</p>",
        "id": 400195357,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Arlin",
        "timestamp": 1699040411
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The general example of a \"locally Boolean algebra\" should be the compact open (hence clopen) subsets of a <em>locally</em> compact Hausdorff totally disconnected space. In the case of your example, that space is <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>S</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">S</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">S</span></span></span></span> with the discrete topology.</p>",
        "id": 400195481,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1699040500
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Hmm, I wonder if it's important that the full downsets are boolean algebras, rather than just that you've got a certain kind of filtered colimit of finite boolean algebras.</p>",
        "id": 400195780,
        "sender_full_name": "Kevin Arlin",
        "timestamp": 1699040632
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>It's a bit tricky to say how the \"locally Boolean algebra\" is built from the various downsets <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">⊥</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi>A</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">[\\bot, A]</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord\">⊥</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">A</span><span class=\"mclose\">]</span></span></span></span>, because the inclusion of one in a bigger one doesn't preserve the negation.</p>",
        "id": 400196194,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1699040830
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Which is also why I didn't give a real definition.</p>",
        "id": 400196214,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1699040845
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I got it!</p>\n<p>The structure I'm looking for is \"commutative associative idempotent (not-necessarily unital) <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">Z</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{Z}_2</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8389em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbb\">Z</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3011em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:0em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">2</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>-algebra!</p>",
        "id": 400196685,
        "sender_full_name": "Joshua Meyers",
        "timestamp": 1699041074
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>(inspired by <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/Boolean+ring\">https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/Boolean+ring</a>)</p>",
        "id": 400196832,
        "sender_full_name": "Joshua Meyers",
        "timestamp": 1699041135
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"280784\">Joshua Meyers</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229199-learning.3A-questions/topic/What.20is.20the.20structure.20of.20.24.24.5Cmathcal.7BP.7D.5E.7B.5Ctext.7Bfin.7D.7D.28S.29.24.24.3F/near/400196685\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>I got it!</p>\n<p>The structure I'm looking for is \"commutative associative idempotent (not-necessarily unital) <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">Z</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{Z}_2</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8389em;vertical-align:-0.15em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbb\">Z</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3011em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:0em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">2</span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.15em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>-algebra!</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>These are fun <span aria-label=\"blush\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f60a\" role=\"img\" title=\"blush\">:blush:</span></p>",
        "id": 400196951,
        "sender_full_name": "Eric Forgy",
        "timestamp": 1699041197
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>But unfortunately, the free such structure on a set <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>S</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">S</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">S</span></span></span></span> is not <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi mathvariant=\"script\">P</mi><mtext>fin</mtext></msup><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>S</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal{P}^{\\text{fin}}(S)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.0991em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08222em;\">P</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8491em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord text mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">fin</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">S</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> but rather <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi mathvariant=\"script\">P</mi><mtext>fin</mtext></msup><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>R</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal{P}^{\\text{fin}}(R)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.0991em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08222em;\">P</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8491em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord text mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">fin</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.00773em;\">R</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>, where <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>R</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">R</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.00773em;\">R</span></span></span></span> is the set of indecomposable regions on a fully generic Venn diagram with one circle for each <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>s</mi><mo>∈</mo><mi>S</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">s\\in S</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.5782em;vertical-align:-0.0391em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">s</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">∈</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">S</span></span></span></span>. More formally, <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>R</mi><mo>≅</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">{</mo><mi>b</mi><mo>:</mo><mi>S</mi><mo>→</mo><mo stretchy=\"false\">{</mo><mn>0</mn><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mn>1</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">}</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∣</mi><mi>b</mi><mo mathvariant=\"normal\">≠</mo><mn>0</mn><mo stretchy=\"false\">}</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">R \\cong \\{b: S\\to \\{0,1\\} | b\\neq 0\\}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.00773em;\">R</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">≅</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">{</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">b</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">:</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">S</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">{</span><span class=\"mord\">0</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span><span class=\"mclose\">}</span><span class=\"mord\">∣</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">b</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\"><span class=\"mrel\"><span class=\"mord vbox\"><span class=\"thinbox\"><span class=\"rlap\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"inner\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mrel\"></span></span></span><span class=\"fix\"></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mrel\">=</span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">0</span><span class=\"mclose\">}</span></span></span></span>.</p>",
        "id": 400200904,
        "sender_full_name": "Joshua Meyers",
        "timestamp": 1699043060
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Wait this only works for finite <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>S</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">S</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">S</span></span></span></span></p>",
        "id": 400201080,
        "sender_full_name": "Joshua Meyers",
        "timestamp": 1699043177
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I wish there was some way to specify that the generators are disjoint</p>",
        "id": 400201607,
        "sender_full_name": "Joshua Meyers",
        "timestamp": 1699043497
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Kinda related to <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229136-theory.3A-category-theory/topic/Ref.20request.3A.20monad.20for.20boolean.20algebras\">this thread</a>.</p>",
        "id": 400206335,
        "sender_full_name": "Ralph Sarkis",
        "timestamp": 1699046275
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"280784\">Joshua Meyers</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229199-learning.3A-questions/topic/What.20is.20the.20structure.20of.20.24.24.5Cmathcal.7BP.7D.5E.7B.5Ctext.7Bfin.7D.7D.28S.29.24.24.3F/near/400189068\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>Yes that is true! But what if you want to consider set difference and/or symmetric difference part of the structure?</p>\n<p>As a matter of fact, how do you even get binary intersections this way?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Those are good questions! But those operations are not natural with respect to the obvious covariant functor sending <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>S</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">S</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">S</span></span></span></span> to <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi mathvariant=\"script\">P</mi><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">f</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi></mrow></msup><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>S</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal{P}^{\\mathrm{fin}}(S)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.0991em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08222em;\">P</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8491em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathrm mtight\">fin</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">S</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>, right?   So they're inherently different from finitary unions.</p>",
        "id": 400207772,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1699047301
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I guess I'm suggesting that the categorical viewpoint on \"the operations possessed by <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi mathvariant=\"script\">P</mi><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">f</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">n</mi></mrow></msup><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>S</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal{P}^{\\mathrm{fin}}(S)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.0991em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08222em;\">P</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8491em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathrm mtight\">fin</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">S</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span>\" should consider the question about how these operations get along with maps.</p>",
        "id": 400208110,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1699047539
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>By the way, we can make <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>S</mi><mo>↦</mo><mi mathvariant=\"script\">P</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>S</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">S \\mapsto \\mathcal{P}(S)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6943em;vertical-align:-0.011em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">S</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">↦</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08222em;\">P</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">S</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> into both a covariant and a contravariant functor from <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">t</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathsf{Set}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathsf\">Set</span></span></span></span></span> to <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">t</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathsf{Set}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathsf\">Set</span></span></span></span></span>, via images and inverse images.  This complicates the discussion in fascinating ways.    <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>S</mi><mo>↦</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"script\">P</mi><mtext>fin</mtext></msup><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>S</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">S \\mapsto \\mathcal{P}^{\\textrm{fin}}(S)</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6943em;vertical-align:-0.011em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">S</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">↦</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.0991em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08222em;\">P</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8491em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord text mtight\"><span class=\"mord textrm mtight\">fin</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.05764em;\">S</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span></span></span></span> only gets to be a covariant functor from <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">t</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathsf{Set}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathsf\">Set</span></span></span></span></span> to <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">t</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathsf{Set}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathsf\">Set</span></span></span></span></span>,  not a contravariant one, since the inverse image of a finite subset under a function needn't be finite.  But you can make it into a contravariant functor from <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">F</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">n</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">t</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathsf{FinSet}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathsf\">FinSet</span></span></span></span></span> to <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">F</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">n</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">t</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathsf{FinSet}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathsf\">FinSet</span></span></span></span></span>.</p>",
        "id": 400208684,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1699047862
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>It can also be a contravariant functor on the category with sets as objects and functions with finite fibers as morphisms.  This is almost by definition so it (the category equipped with the contravariant functor) probably has some nice universal property with regard to <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi mathvariant=\"script\">P</mi><mtext>fin</mtext></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathcal{P}^{\\text{fin}}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8491em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathcal\" style=\"margin-right:0.08222em;\">P</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.8491em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord text mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">fin</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> on <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">t</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathsf{Set}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathsf\">Set</span></span></span></span></span> ...</p>",
        "id": 400263251,
        "sender_full_name": "James Deikun",
        "timestamp": 1699080924
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>It's almost the opposite of the Kleisli category</p>",
        "id": 400293319,
        "sender_full_name": "Matteo Capucci (he/him)",
        "timestamp": 1699099514
    }
]